SIMPLE: bowdlerize
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Bowdlerize
<hw>Bowd"ler*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Bowdlerized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Bowdlerizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[After
Dr. Thomas <etsep>Bowdler</etsep>, an English physician, who published
an expurgated edition of Shakespeare in 1818.]</ety> <def>To expurgate,
as a book, by omitting or modifying the parts considered offensive; to
remove morally objectionable parts; -- said of literary texts.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> bowdlerise, expurgate, shorten, cut.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is a grave defect in the splendid tale of Tom Jones . . . that
a <qex>Bowdlerized</qex> version of it would be hardly intelligible as a
tale.</q> <rj><qau>F. Harrison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Bowd`ler*i*za"tion</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
-- <wf>Bowd"ler*ism</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>bowed</ent>⟦br⟧
